{
  "local_port": 39236,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do you reduce the magnification of your screen?",
  "response": "To reduce the magnification of your screen, you can follow these steps depending on your operating system:\n\n### For Windows:\n1. **Using Keyboard Shortcuts:**\n   - Press `Windows key` + `\u2013` (minus key) to zoom out. You can press this combination multiple times until you reach your desired level of magnification.\n   - To exit the magnification mode completely, press `Windows key` + `Esc`.\n\n2. **Using Settings:**\n   - Press `Windows key` + `I` to open Settings.\n   - Go to `Ease of Access`.\n   - Select `Magnifier` from the left sidebar.\n   - Under `Magnifier`, you can adjust the zoom level using the slider or choose to turn off the magnifier.\n\n### For macOS:\n1. **Using Keyboard Shortcuts:**\n   - Press `Command` + `Option` + `\u2013` (minus key) to zoom out. Repeat as necessary.\n   - To disable zoom completely, press `Command` + `Option` + `8`.\n\n2. **Using System Preferences:**\n   - Click on the Apple menu and select `System Preferences`.\n   - Go to `Accessibility`.\n   - Select `Zoom` from the left sidebar.\n   - You can adjust the zoom settings here or turn off the zoom feature.\n\n### For Linux (GNOME):\n1. **Using Keyboard Shortcuts:**\n   - Press `Super` (Windows key) + `\u2013` (minus key) to zoom out.\n   - To disable zoom, press `Super` + `0`.\n\n2. **Using Settings:**\n   - Open `Settings`.\n   - Go to `Accessibility`.\n   - Select `Zoom` and adjust the settings or turn it off.\n\nThese steps should help you reduce the magnification of your screen across different operating systems. If you are using a different desktop environment or have specific accessibility software installed, the steps might vary slightly.",
